ae 1.3.0<3;1>
========<5;1>
A minimalist version of `vi(1)`.  It is an example of the "Buffer Gap" method outlined in the [The Craft Of Text Editing](http://www.finseth.com/craft/) used by<7;2>
many Emacs style editors.<10;1>
Usage<11;1>
-----<13;5>
ae [filename]<15;1>
Read or create a text file; default filename is `a.txt`.  Text files consists of<16;2>
lines of printable text, tabs, or newline characters.  A physical line can be of arbitrary length and is delimited by either a newline or the end of file.  Tab<18;2>
stops are every eight columns.  The behaviour of non-printable characters may vary depending on the implementation of the Curses library, `stty(1)` settings, or terminal emulator.<23;1>
